    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            A compound inequality is formed by combining two or more simple inequalities using the words <m>\textbf{AND}</m> or <m>\textbf{OR}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="i)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\textbf{"AND" Inequalities (Intersection)}</m>: Both conditions must be true at the same time. It represents a continuous range of values. For example, <m>x \gt-2</m> AND <m>x \lt 5</m> is usually written as a single statement: <m>-2 \lt x \lt 5</m> (read as "<m>x</m> is greater than <m>-2</m> and less than <m>5</m>").
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\textbf{"OR" Inequalities (Union)}</m>: Only one of the conditions needs to be true. The solutions go in opposite directions and cannot be written as a single combined statement. For example, a discount ticket applies if your age <m>a</m> is <m>\lt 12</m> OR <m>\ge 60</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\textbf{Solving Continuous Inequalities}</m>: If an inequality has three parts (e.g., <m>a \lt x \lt b</m>), you can solve it by splitting it into two separate inequalities using "AND", solving each, and then recombining the final answer.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the following compound inequality:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>x \le 4 \text{ AND } 2x -10 \lt 6</me>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The first inequality is already solved: <m>x \le 4</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                For the second inequality, we can solve it as follows:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>2x - 10 &amp; \lt 6</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x &amp;\lt 16</mrow>
                    <mrow>x &amp;\lt 8</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Now we combine the two inequalities to get the final answer:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x</m> must be <m>\textbf{greater than}-5</m> AND <m>x</m> must be <m>\textbf{less than or equal to } 4</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>-5 \lt x \le 4</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve for <m>x</m> in the inequality:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>2x + 4 \lt 5 + 3x \lt 8 + 2x</me>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First we split the compound inequality into two separate simple inequalities:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>2x + 4 \lt 5 + 3x \text{ and } 5 + 3x \lt 8 + 2x</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                The first inequality we solve as follows:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>2x + 4 &amp;\lt 5 + 3x</mrow>
                    <mrow>4 &amp;\lt 5 + x</mrow>
                    <mrow>-1 &amp;\lt x</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                We can also write it as <m>x \gt -1</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Then the second inequality we solve as follows:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>5 + 3x &amp;\lt 8 + 2x</mrow>
                    <mrow>3x &amp;\lt 3 + 2x</mrow>
                    <mrow>x &amp;\lt 3</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Now we combine the two inequalities to get the final answer:
            </p>
            <p>
                Since <m>x</m> must be <m>\textbf{greater than}-1</m> AND <m>x</m> must be <m>\textbf{less than } 3</m>, we write:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>-1 \lt x \lt 3</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A matatu travelling from Nairobi to Nakuru takes <m>t</m> hours. Traffic regulations state that the trip must take a minimum of <m>2</m> hours (to prevent over-speeding) but strictly less than <m>4</m> hours. If the time taken is represented by the expression <m>t = \frac{x + 10}{30}</m>. Write a compound inequality to represent this situation and solve for <m>x</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First we set up the continuous inequality using the given limits:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>2 \lt t \lt 4</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Substituting the expression for <m>t</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>2 \lt \frac{x + 10}{30} \lt 4</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Then, we multiply all three parts by <m>30</m> to eliminate the denominator:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>2 \times 30 \lt x + 10 \lt 4 \times 30</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>60 \lt x + 10 \lt 120</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Now, we can have <m>2</m> separate inequalities:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>60 \lt x + 10 \text{ and } x + 10 \lt 120</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                So we solve the first inequality:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>60 &amp;\lt x + 10</mrow>
                    <mrow>50 &amp;\lt x</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                then we solve the second inequality:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x + 10 &amp;\lt 120</mrow>
                    <mrow>x &amp;\lt 110</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
             <p>
                Then when we combine the two inequalities we get:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>50 \lt x \lt 110</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

